<br>
I often wonder what would be if I had been a more mature person...<br>
<br>
From reading the post, I got the impression that you felt the seperation was just a long distance relationship.  That she would return some day and things would pick up where they left off.  Unfortunately, it rarely works that way.  Most people feel a need to be near, someone.  Talking on the phone and writing emails can only do so much when truly trying to &quot;share.&quot;  It puts alot of strain on relationships.<br>
<br>
My advice:  Don't seek her out.  Try to remember the good times; and think well of her.  Yes, she hurt you deeply, but she may have felt hurt by your choice of not going with her and may of taken it as a sign of some sort.<br>
<br>
I don't believe in the concept of &quot;one&quot; true love.<br>
<br>
Tatter D'Malion <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uwaasak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Waasak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#CC9900>(8/14/01 12:35:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haunting dreams of ex girlfriends</span><hr size=1>   Understanding of the way people think is not easy.  We are all different and everyone has encountered similar situations, but they are almost always unique in there own way.  I have done some heartbreaking, and have had my heartbroken as well.  Things happen, it's easy for those of us without this current situation to say get over it and move on.  However, it isn't always that easy a thing to do.  The emptiness left in your heart isn't an easy thing to get over and there is only one thing to mend wounds of the heart and that is time.  Time cures a lot of ailments, broken bones, sickness, and broken hearts, their is no estimated time of recovery from a broken heart.  The last time my heart was broken I found myself getting in conversations with new women and people and after about 2 minutes I would lose any interest in the conversation at hand, because I would find myself thinking about the past.  It wasn't until I was finally able to hold a conversation and interest in a new person for more than 15 minutes that I would realize that yes, indeed I was finally over my broken heart.<br>
<br>
  My advice is to not spend much time alone, go hang with some friends, talk about everyday type stuff and just try to move on as best you can.  You must cherish what you had in the past with her and you can keep those memories forever, but when you torment yourself over what may never be again you are only making matters worse.  Lighten up a little go out with some friends and have a good time.  I find the times I have the most fun is when I am not out looking to meet someone new.  Just out having fun with friends, family and realizing that there are people that care plenty for me, without that ex-gf in my life.  Hope you can find some consolation in the advice offered you in these pages here. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umahannon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mahannon </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#CC9900>(8/15/01 12:13:33 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haunting dreams of ex girlfriends</span><hr size=1> Ooh, my turn to give an anecdote.  Similar situation with different details.  In this case it was just a friendship that went down the tubes, but we were fairly close.<br>
<br>
I'd known her about 4 years, I'd been mildly infatuated with her, but it wore off shortly as she wasn't really the sort of woman that I pursue romantically.  Nonetheless we had a fair amount in common and our personalities complemented each other, she also shared my cynical, contemptuous view of our peers.  She was already involved with another guy, and I was exploring the delights of underaged drinking and chasing skirts.  We enjoyed each other's company and we were both content to leave it at that.  However, somewhere along the line something went wrong, although to this day I don't know what.  Rarely would a day go by where we would pass 2 dozen words between us, when heretofore we'd spent hours having conversations about art, politics, music, what have you.  Seeing as she was my friend, I was naturally somewhat concerned, and I begin making circumspect inquiries to see if I couldn't coax out of her what the problem was.  No dice, my (to my mind) delicate prodding earned me the combination stonewall and cold shoulder.  At this point I'm extremely confused, and more than a little angry.  Confused, because I figure if she would be talking to anyone about it, it would be me, and angry due to my own inability to figure it out what it is on my own, and her mysterious and unprecedented decision to summarily end our friendship of four years.  Eventually I just gave it up as a lost cause, confrontation got me precisely nothing, and even though we moved in the same circles it was awkward and uncomfortable to be around her.  Then one day, completely out of the blue, she pulled me aside and told me, in a dubiously cheerful tone, that she'd been diagnosed with clinical depression.  Having dropped this bombshell on me, she turned on her heel and walked away.  After that, nothing for over a month.  Then, just before winter vacation she did the same bit, grabbing me by the hand for a private tete a tete.  Two years later, this is the only part it still hurts to remember, in light of what happened after.  She told me that was allright, and that I shouldn't worry about her, she would be able to take care of herself.  The next time I saw her it was like talking to one of the pod people from Invasion of the Body Snatchers, everything about her was eerily familiar, but somehow horribly wrong.  It was as if her entire personality had changed, that is except for in respect to me.  I learned through third parties that she'd been put on meds and had been going to therapy, hence her drastic change in temperament.  I spent a lot of time being pissed off at myself, at her, at society in general; it all just seemed so horribly unfair.  I tried to attempt some sort of reconcilliation, but things just weren't the same.  There just wasn't room left for me in her new mood stabilized and analyzed life, she didn't need a bitter pessimist hanging around cramping her style.  In retrospect I took a lot of it out on my other friends, and if any of them happen to be reading this and recognize me from the events described I'd like to say I'm sorry guys, you took a lot of misdirected @#%$ you didn't deserve.  Later that year I left to go to college in Boston, and I decided to make a mostly clean break.  I never thought about trying to get a hold of her after that, I'd already said everything I could say and I didn't feel like reliving the whole experience over again.  Eventually I got over it, and I can look back on it without feeling bitter.  In the end she just didn't need me anymore, and as little as I like to say it, I didn't need her anymore either.  If I were to see her on the other side of a crowded street tommorrow, I think I'd just keep on walking.  Some things are best left alone. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usepnevermore.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SepNevermore</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Runs with Scissors</span><br>  Posts: 10